Dorynota parallela

has the anterior pronotal margin medially acuminate and elevated; scutellum slightly projected over posterior angle of pronotum; elytral spinose projection slightly shorter than body height; claws (
Fig. 38
) parallel, with the left claw slightly shorter than right claw; male terminalia (
Figs. 88–93
) with median lobe (
Fig. 88
) at an obtuse angle; tegmen (
Figs. 89–90
) not wellsclerotized, except for basal portion of manubrium, with arms flattened laterally, acuminate at apex; internal sac (
Figs. 91–93
) membranous, highly convoluted dorsally, with two bags bulging dorsally (
Figs. 91–92
); surface and inner walls sparsely armed with spicules and two sinuous arms (
Fig. 93
) laterally to apex. Female terminalia (
Figs. 94–97
) with sternite VIII (
Fig. 95
) apodeme 1.7 times longer than sternite width, narrow, and with subparallel lateral margins medially; spermatheca (
Fig. 94
) falcate, with truncate base and posterior third abruptly tapering towards apex; spermathecal duct long and coiled. In 

Paranota
species

, the pronotum has the anterior margin medially emarginated or rounded; scutellum not projected over posterior angle of pronotum; claws (
Fig. 38
) subparallel with the left claw distinctly shorter than right claw; male terminalia (
Figs. 39–41
, 
52–56
, 
62–64
, 
72–74
) with tegmen well-sclerotized, arms not flattened laterally, apex truncate; median lobe at a 90° angle; female terminalia (
Figs. 43–46
, 
65–68
, 
78–81
) with sternite VIII apodeme as long as the width of sternite, narrow at base; spermatheca U-shaped, rounded at base, tapered continuously towards apex; spermathecal duct long and strongly coiled.
